": false, "mention": "carcinomas", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999933242797852, "span": {"begin": 587, "end": 597}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:653108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9917906522750854, "span": {"begin": 613, "end": 616}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mutant cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6830765604972839, "span": {"begin": 787, "end": 799}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumors", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999938011169434, "span": {"begin": 829, "end": 835}}], "text": "Clonally expanded cells (foci of cellular alteration &ndash; either eosinophilic, basophilic or clear cell) have been shown to be increased at tumorigenic dose levels of CAR activators such as phenobarbital, TCPOBOP and metofluthrin. As discussed for earlier key events, the CAR-mediated events that lead to an increase in altered foci lead to a greater abundance of cells with mutations in their DNA that are less responsive to normal cell-cell signaling and control mechanisms. As a result, these foci are considered preneoplastic lesions, and can progress with time into adenomas and carcinomas. The continued CAR-mediated stimulus for increased cell proliferation within these foci (e.g. as demonstrated in studies by Kolaja et al., 1996b) will also provide an environment where the mutant cells can survive and develop into tumors.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:49:10 +0000 2026"}